13. Step 5 — Test Without CA Bundle
We test TLS from the no-ca-bundle pod.
Command:
oc exec no-ca-bundle -- \
openssl s_client -connect server.network-svccerts.svc:443
Explanation
Part	Meaning
oc exec	run command in pod
no-ca-bundle	pod name
openssl s_client	test TLS connection
connect	service address
Service DNS format:
service.namespace.svc
Here:
server.network-svccerts.svc
________________________________________
Result
Error:
self signed certificate in certificate chain
Why?
Because:
Client does not trust the cluster CA.
________________________________________
14. Step 6 — Inject OpenShift CA Bundle
OpenShift provides a way to automatically inject the cluster CA.
We use ConfigMap annotation.
________________________________________
Create ConfigMap
oc create configmap ca-bundle
Creates empty configmap.
________________________________________
Annotate It
oc annotate configmap ca-bundle \
service.beta.openshift.io/inject-cabundle=true
This tells OpenShift:
Inject cluster CA certificate into this ConfigMap.
________________________________________
15. Verify ConfigMap
oc get configmap ca-bundle -o yaml
You will see:
data:
  service-ca.crt:
This is the OpenShift service CA certificate.
________________________________________
16. Step 7 — Mount CA Bundle in Client Pod
Client must trust server certificate.
So we mount CA bundle.
________________________________________
Client YAML Key Section
volumeMounts:
- mountPath: /etc/pki/ca-trust/extracted/pem
  name: trusted-ca
Meaning:
Mount CA certificates into container trust store.
________________________________________
Define Volume
volumes:
- configMap:
    name: ca-bundle
    items:
    - key: service-ca.crt
      path: tls-ca-bundle.pem
  name: trusted-ca
Meaning:
Use configmap as volume.
________________________________________
